9. On December 28 [1737] he left London. It was on the 29th that he first preached without notes. December 30 he went on board;
The Whitaker, from Purfleet. but it was above a month before they cleared the land. One happy effect of their very slow passage he mentions in April following: ‘Blessed be God, we now live very comfortably in the great cabin. We talk of little else but God and Christ. […] And scarce a word is heard among us when together but what has reference to our fall in the first, and our new birth in the Second Adam.’
Cf. George Whitefield’s Journals, ed., Iain Murray (London, Banner of Truth Trust, 1960), p. 149. It seems likewise to have been a peculiar providence that he should spend a little time at Gibraltar, where both citizens and soldiers, high and low, young and old, acknowledged the day of their visitation.
